In case you‚Äôre settling into winter and lamenting not having read everything The Atlantic has published this year, you‚Äôre in luck. I‚Äôve created a list of stories you may have missed that are very much worth your time. The assortment ranges widely: eating an organ feast in Mark Twain‚Äôs Paris, experiencing a comedy-show adventure in Riyadh, drifting after a shipwreck in the Pacific, and diving into the secrets of the Inca empire. ‚ÄúWhat Parents of Boys Should Know‚Äù sparked many conversations in my group chats, as did this photo of Abraham Lincoln‚Äôs ear being cleaned. There are stories that contextualized a chaotic moment for the American experiment, drawing deeply on history. I hope you‚Äôll spend time with this selection, and I would love to hear what you think. Send me a note: btharoor@theatlantic.com . I Watched Stand-Up in Saudi Arabia By Helen Lewis What the surreal Riyadh Comedy Festival foretold about the kingdom‚Äôs future The New Rasputins By Anne Applebaum Anti-science mysticism is enabling autocracy around the globe. America and Its Universities Need a New Social Contract By Danielle Allen Fifty dollars for STEM, five cents for citizenship‚Äîthat‚Äôs how America apportions its education dollars. Our beleaguered universities must redress the balance‚Äîhelping the country and themselves. What Parents of Boys Should Know By Joshua Coleman Daughters tend to receive higher levels of affection and patience at home than sons. But the sons might need it more. Is This the Worst-Ever Era of American Pop Culture? By Spencer Kornhaber An emerging critical consensus argues that we‚Äôve entered a cultural dark age. I‚Äôm not so sure. My Shipwreck Story By Alec Frydman On my first time out as a commercial fisherman, my boat sank, my captain died, and I was left adrift and alone in the Pacific. An Innocent Abroad in Mark Twain‚Äôs Paris By Caity Weaver My quest for a true literary experience resulted in choucroute , a surprise organ feast, an epiphany at the L